final_answer("The provided JavaScript snippet is erroneous because the loop condition `i <= str.length` causes it to iterate one time too many (indices are 0 to length-1), returning `str.length + 1`.

Corrected loop version:
```javascript
function correctStringLength(str) {
  let length = 0;
  for (let i = 0; i < str.length; i++) {
    length++;
  }
  return length;
}
```

The standard and most reliable way is using the `.length` property:
```javascript
function correctStringLength(str) {
  return str.length;
}
```

Crucially, `.length` counts UTF-16 code units. This means Unicode surrogate pairs (like emojis) are counted as two characters. To correctly count Unicode characters (code points), use `Array.from()`:
```javascript
function correctStringLength(str) {
    return Array.from(str).length;
}
```")
