final_answer("To eliminate repetitive alphabetic symbols in Java while preserving order, the most efficient procedure is using a `LinkedHashSet` from the Java Collections Framework. 

Procedure:
1. Convert the input string into a character array using `.toCharArray()`.
2. Iterate through the characters and attempt to add each to a `LinkedHashSet<Character>`. Since a `Set` cannot contain duplicates, the `.add()` method returns `false` if the character is already present.
3. Use a `StringBuilder` to append only the characters that were successfully added to the set.
4. Convert the `StringBuilder` back to a string.

Example Implementation:
```java
import java.util.LinkedHashSet;
import java.util.Set;

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String text = \"This is a test text with repetitive characters.\";
        System.out.println(removeDuplicates(text));
    }

    static String removeDuplicates(String str) {
        Set<Character> set = new LinkedHashSet<>();
        StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder();
        for (char c : str.toCharArray()) {
            if (set.add(c)) {
                sb.append(c);
            }
        }
        return sb.toString();
    }
}
```

This approach ensures O(n) time complexity and preserves the original sequence of the first occurrence of each character.")
